    <section id="spreadsheet-nightmare">
      <p>
        The spreadsheet is the silent killer of the scaling home builder. It starts innocently—a VLOOKUP for material pricing here, a basic macro for labor hours there. But as you transition from three starts per year to thirty, that "flexible" tool becomes a fragile liability. 
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Key-Man Risk</strong> is the first symptom. When only one person understands the interlocking logic of a 50MB estimating workbook, your entire preconstruction pipeline depends on their presence. If they leave, the tribal knowledge governing your <strong>Quantity Takeoffs (QTO)</strong> goes with them.
      </p>
      <p>
        Then comes <strong>Version Hell</strong>. When the "Master_Estimator_v4_REVISED_JAN2025.xlsx" is copied across three different estimator desktops, material price updates never synchronize. You're bidding 2025 projects using 2024 supply chain costs, unknowingly signing contracts for <strong>margin erosion</strong> before the first shovel hits the ground.
      </p>
    </section>

    <!-- CTA 1 -->
    <div class="my-16 p-8 rounded-3xl bg-[#2D2442] text-white shadow-xl relative overflow-hidden group">
      <div class="absolute top-0 right-0 w-32 h-32 bg-purple-500/10 rounded-full -mr-16 -mt-16 blur-2xl group-hover:bg-purple-500/20 transition-all"></div>
